<Product
  name="Ontologyzer"
  description="Automated ontology extraction and structuring engine. Extracts entities, relations, and taxonomies from unstructured text — turning raw documents into machine-readable knowledge graphs."
  status="Available"
  license="Commercial license"
>

<h2>What it does</h2>

<p>
  Ontologyzer takes unstructured text &mdash; documents, articles, reports, transcripts &mdash; and produces structured ontologies: entities, their types, the relationships between them, and the taxonomic hierarchies that organize them. It does what tools like LangExtract promise, but with extraction pipelines that actually hold up on real-world, messy documents.
</p>

<hr />

<h2>Core capabilities</h2>

<div class="feature-block">
  <div class="feature-label">Extraction</div>
  <h4>Entity and relation extraction</h4>
  <p>
    Identifies named entities (people, organizations, locations, concepts, technical terms) and the relationships between them (reports-to, part-of, caused-by, depends-on). Goes beyond simple NER by resolving coreferences, disambiguating entities across documents, and inferring implicit relationships from context.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="feature-block">
  <div class="feature-label">Structure</div>
  <h4>Taxonomy generation</h4>
  <p>
    Automatically builds hierarchical category structures from extracted entities. Groups related concepts, identifies is-a and part-of relationships, and produces clean taxonomies that can be directly imported into knowledge management systems, search engines, or graph databases.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="feature-block">
  <div class="feature-label">Quality</div>
  <h4>Consistency and validation</h4>
  <p>
    Cross-references extracted facts across multiple documents to identify contradictions, redundancies, and gaps. Assigns confidence scores to extracted relations. Flags ambiguous extractions for human review rather than silently guessing.
  </p>
</div>

<hr />

<h2>How it works</h2>

<p>
  The extraction pipeline runs in three stages:
</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Document processing:</strong> Ingests raw text, PDF, HTML, or structured formats. Handles section detection, table extraction, and reference resolution.</li>
  <li><strong>Semantic extraction:</strong> A multi-pass extraction engine identifies entities, relations, and hierarchies. Each pass builds on the previous one &mdash; entity extraction informs relation extraction, which informs taxonomy construction.</li>
  <li><strong>Ontology assembly:</strong> Merges extractions across documents into a unified ontology. Resolves entity aliases, deduplicates relations, and produces output in standard formats (OWL, RDF, JSON-LD, or plain JSON).</li>
</ol>

<hr />

<h2>Built for</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Knowledge graph construction from document corpora</li>
  <li>Enterprise search systems that need structured metadata</li>
  <li>Research organizations processing large volumes of publications</li>
  <li>Legal and compliance teams extracting structured data from contracts and regulations</li>
  <li>Content management systems that need automated tagging and categorization</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h2>Output formats</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>OWL / RDF:</strong> Standard semantic web formats for integration with existing knowledge bases</li>
  <li><strong>JSON-LD:</strong> Linked data format for web applications</li>
  <li><strong>Plain JSON:</strong> Simple structured output for custom integrations</li>
  <li><strong>Neo4j / Graph DB:</strong> Direct import into graph databases</li>
</ul>

